3', 'Semantics of FOL
• Domain M: the set of all objects in the world (of interest)
• Interpretation I: includes
– Assign each constant to an object in M
– Define each function of n arguments as a mapping Mn => M
– Define each predicate of n arguments as a mapping Mn => {T, F}
– Therefore, every ground predicate with any instantiation will have a
truth value
– In general there is an infinite number of interpretations because |M| is
infinite
• Define logical connectives: ~, ^, v, =>, <=> as in PL
• De', 'First-order logic
• First-order logic (FOL) models the world in terms of
– Objects, which are things with individual identities
– Properties of objects that distinguish them from other objects
– Relations that hold among sets of objects
– Functions, which are a subset of relations where there is only one
“value” for any given “input”
• Examples:
– Objects: Students, lectures, companies, cars ...
– Relations: Brother-of, bigger-than, outside, part-of, has-color,
occurs-after, owns, visits, preced']
response: First-order logic (FOL) models the world in terms of objects, properties of objects, relations that hold among sets of objects, and functions.
reference: FOL stands for First Order Logic. It models the world in terms of objects, properties, and relations and allows quantification over variables.

response:
Higher-order logic (HOL) allows us to quantify over relations, whereas First-order logic (FOL) only allows to quantify over variables, and variables can only range over objects. HOL enables quantification over functions and predicates, as shown in the examples: 
- Quantifying over functions: ∢f ∢g (f = g) ⇔ (∢x f(x) = g(x))
- Quantifying over predicates: ∢r transitive(r) → (∢xyz) r(x,y) ∙ r(y,z) → r(x,z))
reference: Higher order logic allows quantification over relations and functions, unlike FOL which only quantifies over objects.
